      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; model form uncertainty addressed qualitatively through validation evidence.",
      "rationale": "Formal model-form uncertainty quantification is not required at MRL 2. The SST k-omega turbulence model and Giersiepen hemolysis power-law are standard approaches for blood pump CFD, and their applicability is supported by the validation comparisons documented in the Output Comparison factor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties, boundary conditions, and geometric parameters documented with sources; input uncertainty ranges specified for primary model inputs.",
      "rationale": "All 23 model input parameters are documented in the simulation specification record with literature or measurement sources. Blood analog viscosity (3.5 ± 0.18 mPa·s), density (1056 ± 5 kg/m³), and hemolysis power-law coefficients (C = 3.62×10⁻⁵, α = 2.416, β = 0.785) are specified with uncertainty ranges derived from published experimental data. A screening sensitivity study was conducted during model development to identify which of the 23 inputs produced the largest variation in predicted RH; rotational speed and impeller tip clearance were found to be most influential and were subsequently assigned tighter tolerance bounds in the uncertainty quantification sweep. The UQ analysis propagated ±5% variations across all primary inputs using a Monte Carlo approach with 500 samples, yielding a 95th-percentile RH prediction interval of [0.71, 0.94] against the acceptance threshold of RH < 1.",
